<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-140-664  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 140 664.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Modern Office Technology  March 1989 v34 n3 p68(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Making both film and optical payoff. (computer-assisted documentstorage and retrieval systems) (Alexander andamp; Alexander ServicesInc.)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users can choose between optical disk and microfilm-based systemswhen deciding on a computer-assisted document storage andretrieval system.andP;  One company decided that an optical system wasbest for one area while another area's needs were best met with afilm-based system.andP;  One advantage of microfilm systems is that thedata contained in such a system is admissible in courts of law,unlike optical disk media.andP;  A film-based system also allows datafrom the host mainframe to be downloaded to the Image Searchsystem, so that departments can search through documents usingspecific criteria.andP;  The advantage of an optical system is thatdata can be retrieved instantly and randomly, without thenecessity of going through roles of film.andP;  The optical system alsoprovided a great deal of savings in floor space so that it canstart paying for itself from the first moment of installation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Alexander and Alexander Inc. (automation).andO;Topic:     MicrographicsOptical MemoryAccountingPersonnel ManagementRecords ManagementInsurance AgenciesDocument Management Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Accounting department computer assisted microfilm system. (chart)Benefits department optical disk system. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>